  "prompt": "What does the \"@\" symbol mean in Objective-C?",
  "response": "In Objective-C, the \"@\" symbol is a prefix used for several different purposes, primarily to denote literals and object types. Here are the most common uses of the \"@\" symbol in Objective-C:\n\n1. **String Literals**: When you use `@\"string\"` to create a string, you are creating an instance of `NSString`. For example:\n   ```objective-c\n   NSString *myString = @\"Hello, World!\";\n   ```\n\n2. **Selectors**: In Objective-C, you can define a selector (a method identifier) using the \"@\" symbol. For example:\n   ```objective-c\n   SEL mySelector = @selector(myMethod);\n   ```\n\n3. **NSNumber and Other Literal Objects**: You can use \"@\" to create other literal objects like `NSNumber`, `NSArray`, `NSDictionary`, etc. For example:\n   ```objective-c\n   NSNumber *myNumber = @42; // Creates an NSNumber object\n   NSArray *myArray = @[@\"Item 1\", @\"Item 2\"]; // Creates an NSArray object\n   NSDictionary *myDictionary = @{@\"key\": @\"value\"}; // Creates an NSDictionary object\n   ```\n\n4. **Block Syntax**: When defining a block, the \"@\" symbol may be used to denote a block type in some contexts, though this is less common.\n\n5. **Objective-C Class Types**: When declaring an object pointer, such as `NSString *`, the \"@\" indicates that you're working with an Objective-C object, as opposed to a primitive type (like `int` or `float`).\n\n6. **Preprocessor Directives**: The \"@\" symbol is also used in some preprocessor directives like `@interface` and `@implementation` to define classes and methods.\n\nIn summary, the \"@\" symbol in Objective-C plays a crucial role in denoting object types, creating literals, and defining method selectors.",
